 {"id":"asupersync-me99","title":"[CRITICAL] Fix waker dispatch in reactor poll() implementations","description":"# BUG: Missing Waker Dispatch After Poll

## Severity: CRITICAL

## Problem

Both EpollReactor::poll() (asupersync-79yr) and LabReactor::poll() (asupersync-aewx) retrieve I/O events but **never wake the registered wakers**. This means:

1. Reactor correctly detects "socket X is readable"
2. Converts to Event { token, ready: Interest::READABLE }
3. Returns events to caller
4. **But the future waiting for socket X is NEVER woken**

This is a fundamental bug that will cause all I/O to hang.

## Root Cause

The beads describe poll() returning Events, but the IoDriver/runtime must look up the waker for each token and call `waker.wake()`. This step is missing from the design.

## Required Fix

### Option A: Reactor returns wakers (preferred)

```rust
// In poll() after collecting events:
fn poll(&self, events: &mut Events, timeout: Option<Duration>) -> io::Result<usize> {
    // ... existing event collection ...

    // Wake futures for each event
    let inner = self.inner.lock().unwrap();
    for event in events.iter() {
        if let Some(waker) = inner.wakers.get(event.token) {
            waker.wake_by_ref();
        }
    }

    Ok(events.len())
}
```

### Option B: IoDriver handles waker dispatch

```rust
// In IoDriver::turn():
fn turn(&mut self, timeout: Option<Duration>) -> io::Result<usize> {
    let n = self.reactor.poll(&mut self.events, timeout)?;

    // Dispatch wakers
    for event in self.events.iter() {
        if let Some(waker) = self.token_to_waker.get(&event.token) {
            waker.wake_by_ref();
        }
    }

    Ok(n)
}
```

## Affected Beads

- asupersync-79yr: EpollReactor::poll
- asupersync-aewx: LabReactor Reactor trait
- asupersync-cysj: KqueueReactor (likely same issue)
- asupersync-tk79: IoDriver (should handle waker dispatch)

## Testing

```rust
#[test]
fn test_waker_is_called_on_readable() {
    let woken = Arc::new(AtomicBool::new(false));
    let woken_clone = woken.clone();

    let waker = waker_fn(move || {
        woken_clone.store(true, Ordering::SeqCst);
    });

    // Register socket
    let reg = reactor.register(&socket, Interest::READABLE, waker)?;

    // Make socket readable
    write_to_peer(&socket);

    // Poll
    reactor.poll(&mut events, Some(Duration::from_secs(1)))?;

    // Waker MUST have been called
    assert\!(woken.load(Ordering::SeqCst), "Waker was never called\!");
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] poll() or IoDriver::turn() wakes registered wakers
- [ ] Test verifies waker is called when event fires
- [ ] No double-wake for same event
- [ ] Edge-triggered: waker called once per readiness change","status":"closed","priority":0,"issue_type":"bug","assignee":"VioletPeak","owner":"jeff141421@gmail.com","created_at":"2026-01-18T06:08:34.914796363Z","created_by":"Dicklesworthstone","updated_at":"2026-01-18T06:43:57.020549701Z","closed_at":"2026-01-18T06:43:57.020549701Z","close_reason":"Resolved via Option B (IoDriver handles waker dispatch). IoDriver.turn() already implements waker dispatch correctly by calling waker.wake_by_ref() for each event returned by reactor.poll(). Added test io_driver_dispatches_wakers_on_events that verifies this behavior works end-to-end with LabReactor.","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"asupersync-mf6","title":"[EPIC-TOKIO] Time and Timers (tokio-time equivalent)","description":"# Time and Timer Infrastructure

## Overview
Unified time abstraction supporting both virtual time (lab) and wall time (production) with full budget integration.

## Components

### 1. Time Abstraction
- Instant type (virtual or wall)
- Duration (standard)
- Interval type

### 2. Sleep Operations
- sleep(duration): pause for duration
- sleep_until(instant): pause until instant
- Both respect cancellation

### 3. Interval Timers
- interval(period): repeating timer
- interval_at(start, period): with explicit start
- MissedTickBehavior: Burst, Delay, Skip

### 4. Timeout Integration
- Already have timeout combinator
- Integrate with budget deadlines
- Cascading timeouts through regions

### 5. Wheel Timer (Production)
- Hierarchical timing wheel
- Efficient for many timers
- O(1) insert and expire

### 6. Virtual Time (Lab)
- Controlled time advancement
- No wall-clock dependency
- Deterministic timer ordering

## Budget Integration
- Timers contribute to deadline budget
- Budget exhaustion triggers timeout
- Tropical semiring for deadline propagation

## Cancel-Safety
- Sleep: cancel returns Cancelled
- Interval: cancel stops iteration
- Timeout: cancel propagates to inner

## Lab Runtime
- advance_time(duration)
- set_time(instant)
- Timers fire in deterministic order
